did.head: Records Summary
did.abstract: BU Records: NoZe Brotherhood consists of original copies of The Rope newspaper, clippings, and administrative documents produced by and written about the NoZe Brotherhood, an unofficial, satirical, and secret society at Baylor University.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: The Nose Brothers were founded in the 1920s as a rival to the Baylor Chamber of Commerce and as a satire on men’s social organizations. Although the exact date of the organization’s founding is disputed, it is the oldest men’s social organization at Baylor University. Its annual gala, The Pink Tea, dates back to 1926. The organization has gone by a number of names, including The Nosemen of Truth, The Most Noble Nose Brotherhood of Baylor Barber College, the Nose Brotherhood of the Universe, Unlimited, and, currently, The NoZe Brotherhood. NoZe was spelled with a capitalized “z” after 1965.

The NoZe Brotherhood is governed by "The Book of Holy Law," which stipulates the structure of the organization as well as standards of conduct for its members. All members of the organization adopt humorous, nose-related pseudonyms. Members of the organization were originally called “Nosemen” and are currently called Brothers. The Brotherhood became a secret society in the mid-1960s. Currently, brothers “undress” (wear costumes, often wigs, glasses, and beards or mustaches) to keep their identities hidden.

The NoZe Brotherhood publishes The Rope, a now-monthly newspaper that satirizes a wide variety of subjects, including Baylor University, politicians, Waco, and Christianity. Throughout the 1940s, humorous articles written by members of the Nose Brotherhood were published in The Lariat, Baylor University’s student newspaper. The NoZe Brotherhood began publishing its own satirical, monthly newspaper circa 1950.

Throughout its history, the NoZe Brotherhood has had numerous conflicts with Baylor University administration. The Brotherhood was banned in 1965 when they painted pink and possibly set fire to a bridge over Waco Creek. In December 1978, Baylor University President Abner McCall banned the Brotherhood for publishing and distributing a counterfeit Lariat. In 1999, The Rope parodied a study-abroad program using racial stereotypes, and the Brotherhood was subsequently kicked off campus when it refused to register with the University as a formal organization. Currently, the NoZe Brotherhood is not an official student organization at Baylor University.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection begins in 1929 and ends in 2022. It contains documents produced by and about the NoZe Brotherhood, an unofficial, satirical, and secret society at Baylor University. Series I. Administrative, includes the governing document of the Brotherhood, "The Book of the Holy Law," as well as agreements between Baylor University and the Brotherhood. Series II. Clippings, includes articles about the NoZe Brotherhood published by the Baylor Lariat, the Baylor Line, the Waco Tribune-Herald, the Dallas Morning News, the Houston Chronicle, the Texas Monthly, Esquire, and others. Series III. Correspondence, contains letters and postcards to and from the Brotherhood. The bulk of this collection is Series IV. Literary Productions, which contains advertisements, original artwork, Pink Tea programs, and copies of The Rope Newspaper..
Some materials in the collection were compiled over time by previous Texas Collection staff members and kept in subject files. These materials were added to the collection during processing.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Prior to current processing, this collection was arranged in four large boxes, one legal-paper sized box, and twelve subject files. The four large boxes contained The Rope newspapers, organized chronologically; the legal-paper sized box contained a photocopied version of the book, The Nose Brotherhood Knows (1997), clippings, screenplays, drawings (undated), one microfilm container, and one flash drive; the twelve subject folders contained clippings, artwork, and Baylor University press releases, organized chronologically by decade (1920s-2000s).
The current arrangement is as follows: Series I. Administrative, Series II. Clippings, Series III. Correspondence, and Series IV. Literary Productions.

bioghist.head: Biography/Profile
bioghist.p: This series is arranged chronologically. It contains a 1970 sociology paper on the organizational structure of the Brotherhood; a proposed, 1984 agreement between Baylor University and the Brotherhood; and a 1995 copy of "The Book of the Holy Law." This series is in excellent condition.
